{
  "card_id": "previous_day_high",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Previous Day High",
  "aliases": [
    "Old High",
    "PDH",
    "pdh",
    "Previous Day's High",
    "previous day's high",
    "前日高点"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "The highest price of the prior trading day, plotted as a horizontal line. It acts as a buy-side liquidity draw, reversal level (when swept and closed back inside the prior range), or bullish continuation target (when price closes above). It informs daily bias and frames intraday reversals and expansions.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Mark the previous day's high (PDH) as a horizontal line, optionally extending it from up to three prior days as confluence.",
    "Treat PDH as a buy-side liquidity level; price tends to draw to it unless consolidating.",
    "Classify daily bias as bullish continuation if the daily candle closes above PDH, especially with displacement.",
    "Classify a bearish reversal setup when price sweeps above PDH and the daily candle closes back inside the prior range (wick formation).",
    "Confirm the reversal on a lower time frame via a change in state of delivery before entering (e.g., break below up-close candles).",
    "Use the wick's 0.5 level (midpoint from body high to wick high) to gauge next-day bearish expansion; a shallow wick supports expansion, while a large wick or close above 0.5 negates the reversal.",
    "In a bullish trend, repeated daily sweeps of PDH indicate continuation; in consolidation, PDH may not be reached.",
    "On the 15-minute or 5-minute chart, label the PDH line and note when price forms equal highs or failure swings near it, signaling resting buy-side liquidity.",
    "Use standard deviation projections (2–2.5 level) to corroborate the PDH as a high-probability expansion target when both levels coincide.",
    "Observe whether price touches PDH: if it closes above, it's a bullish bias signal; if it fails to close above and falls back inside, it's a reversal signal.",
    "If price does not touch either PDH or PDL, treat as consolidation and do not establish bias.",
    "When price sweeps PDH and then shows a bearish directional candle or CISD on lower timeframe, confirm reversal.",
    "If price reverses without sweeping PDH, that level becomes a Failure Swing (low resistance liquidity); if it sweeps then reverses, it becomes high resistance liquidity.",
    "Multiple consecutive days where highs are not broken and are close together form a low resistance liquidity zone of multiple Failure Swings.",
    "When correlated assets (e.g., ES and NQ) show one touching PDH while the other does not make a higher high, identify SMT divergence.",
    "Combine with higher timeframe context (e.g., weekly open direction) to validate the level's importance."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "PDH frames daily bias: a close above targets the next PDH, with entries at intraday points of interest (e.g., fair value gaps). A sweep and close inside signals reversal; confirm via lower-timeframe change in state of delivery, then short toward previous day low or standard deviation projections. Wick size and the 0.5 threshold manage expectations. Avoid trading PDH during consolidation or after it was already swept in the session. In bullish New York Manipulation profile, PDH is the primary take-profit target after a manipulation sweep lower and confirmed CISD.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Expecting a reversal at PDH without lower-timeframe change in state of delivery confirmation, or entering immediately on a close below PDH without distinguishing retracement vs. reversal.",
    "Treating every touch of PDH as a reversal, especially after only one or two expansion days; three expansion days make a reversal more probable.",
    "Looking for bullish continuation or longs into PDH during consolidation phases or when overall structure is bearish.",
    "Targeting PDH after it has already been swept during the session (e.g., Asia) or ignoring resting liquidity above PDH (equal highs) that may draw price further.",
    "Expecting significant expansion beyond PDH when the reversal wick is large or when price closes back above the 0.5 wick level, invalidating the bearish bias.",
    "Ignoring the daily bias framework and bouncing between models, or not adjusting stop widths for instruments prone to re-sweeps near PDH.",
    "Only looking at whether price touches PDH without checking if it closes above – need close outside to confirm bias.",
    "Forcing a bias when price sweeps both PDH and PDL in the same session – wait for clearer close signal.",
    "Entering before price actually sweeps PDH, ignoring the need for liquidity clearance.",
    "Ignoring higher timeframe context (e.g., weekly open direction) and trading solely on PDH sweep.",
    "Not waiting for lower timeframe CISD confirmation before entering at the daily level.",
    "Treating PDH as a valid bullish target after it has already been swept (now high resistance liquidity).",
    "Ignoring whether PDL has been swept, and relying solely on PDH without considering the high/low resistance liquidity pairing.",
    "Acting on SMT divergence at PDH without waiting for structure alignment or other confirmation.",
    "Using SMT divergence at PDH as a primary trade reason without higher timeframe bias support."
  ],
